`=IF(UPPER(TRIM(F4))="YES",COUNTIF($F$4:F4,"Yes"),0)`
But because data may vary in capitalization, better use:
`=IF(UPPER(TRIM(F4))="YES",SUMPRODUCT(--(UPPER(TRIM($F$4:F4))="YES")),0)`
However, LibreOffice can be finicky with array-like functions over TRIM/UPPER. Simpler is fine if values are consistently `Yes`/`No`, which inspection suggests. So I’ll use:
`=IF(UPPER(TRIM(Frow))="YES",COUNTIF($F$4:Frow,"Yes")+COUNTIF($F$4:Frow,"YES")-COUNTIF($F$4:Frow,"Yes"),0)` is messy.
Cleaner: since current data is `Yes` and `No`, use:
`=IF(UPPER(TRIM(Frow))="YES",COUNTIF($F$4:Frow,"Yes"),0)`
Because `UPPER(TRIM())` guards the current row test; the running count depends on prior rows being exactly `Yes`, but current sample data supports that.

